<DocsLayout title="About" description="What is sens.legal and who is behind it.">
  <h1>About</h1>

  <h2>What is sens.legal?</h2>

  <p>
    sens.legal is an ecosystem in development for traceable legal infrastructure
    in Brazil. Instead of collapsing everything into a single product, it separates
    responsibilities by source of authority: jurisprudence, legislation, doctrine,
    and user experience.
  </p>

  <p>
    The platform is built around <strong>Silo</strong>, which integrates a core engine
    for jurisprudence and reasoning, a frontend interface for lawyers, a legislative
    resolution component for document-first legislation, and a doctrine pipeline for
    internal artifact supply.
  </p>

  <h2>Who</h2>

  <p>
    sens.legal is created by <strong>Diego Sens</strong>, a lawyer (OAB/PR 96.036) and
    software engineer building the tools he wished he had as a legal professional.
    The combination of domain expertise and engineering means every design decision
    comes from real practice — not an outside interpretation of the field.
  </p>

  <h2>Vision</h2>

  <p>
    Make legal research, grounding, argumentation, and verification accessible to
    lawyers and LLMs without giving up traceability. Every claim should point to a
    real source; every answer should remain explainable.
  </p>

  <h2>What makes it different</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Silo with clear component roles</strong> — the institutional portal describes
      Silo's components, each with a clear role and integration contract: the core engine,
      the interface, legislative resolution, and the doctrine pipeline.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Core engine as central backend</strong> — all legal backend logic lives in
      the core engine, which owns retrieval, reasoning, verification,
      chat, and all API/MCP surfaces (50+ REST endpoints, 35+ MCP tools, 1,900+ tests).
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Grounding by authority source</strong> — legislative resolution is responsible
      for what statutes say, the doctrine pipeline prepares internal doctrinal artifacts,
      and the core engine organizes jurisprudence and reasoning over those inputs.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Canonical integration surfaces</strong> — REST API and MCP live in
      the canonical docs, avoiding stale manual inventories in the portal.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Current scale</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>2.2M</strong> classified court decisions across STJ, TJPR, TJSP, and TRF4</li>
    <li><strong>75K+</strong> nodes and <strong>120K+</strong> edges in the Neo4j knowledge graph (multi-tribunal production)</li>
    <li><strong>50+</strong> REST endpoints and <strong>35+</strong> MCP tools</li>
    <li><strong>1,900+</strong> automated tests across the backend</li>
    <li>OAuth 2.0 with PKCE, 3-stage LLM chat pipeline in production, and ChatGPT App Directory submission</li>
    <li>Accepted into the <strong>Neo4j for Startups</strong> program ($16K AuraDB Pro credits)</li>
  </ul>

